<!--
  quota-by-key-monthly.xml
  Per-tenant MONTHLY token chargeback ceiling. Pair with llm-token-limit
  (per-minute throttling) — they answer DIFFERENT questions:

    llm-token-limit with tokens-per-minute (already in workshop-llm-policy.xml)
       ↳ "How fast can a tenant burn tokens?"  (smooths bursts, protects backend)
    llm-token-limit with token-quota + token-quota-period (this fragment)
       ↳ "How many tokens can a tenant spend per MONTH?"  (chargeback ceiling)

  Why two stacked llm-token-limit calls work:
    Each llm-token-limit policy maintains its own counter scoped to its
    `counter-key` AND its window. APIM evaluates them in declaration order
    — the first one to trip wins. Per MS Learn the policy supports
    `tokens-per-minute` (rate limit, 429 on trip) OR
    `token-quota` + `token-quota-period` (quota, 403 on trip), or both:
    https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/api-management/llm-token-limit-policy#attributes

    token-quota-period accepts: Hourly | Daily | Weekly | Monthly | Yearly.
    The window start is the UTC timestamp truncated to that unit, so
    `Monthly` resets at midnight UTC on the 1st.

  How chargeback flows downstream:
    1. This policy adds `x-quota-remaining` to every response.
    2. Your llm-emit-token-metric policy (already applied) tags each metric
       with the same Subscription ID counter-key.
    3. Finance dashboard joins App Insights customMetrics on Subscription ID
       to compute monthly burn and bill back.

  In BFSI you typically grant DIFFERENT tenants DIFFERENT ceilings. To do
  that, swap `token-quota="2000000"` for a policy expression that looks the
  value up per Subscription.Id (Cosmos DB / Key Vault). See enterprise
  patterns doc Pattern 4.
-->
<llm-token-limit
    counter-key="@(context.Subscription.Id)"
    token-quota="2000000"
    token-quota-period="Monthly"
    estimate-prompt-tokens="false"
    remaining-quota-tokens-header-name="x-quota-remaining"
    retry-after-header-name="x-quota-retry-after-seconds" />
